Scope of the Standard

Shunyaya Behavioral Mathematics (SBM) defines a deterministic structural behavioral framework governing ordered system evolution under replay-verifiable discipline.

SBM establishes:

Conservative collapse invariant:

phi((m,a,s)) = m

Deterministic bounded horizon:

H >= 1

Window discipline:

W_H(t) = {t-H+1, ..., t}

Deterministic structural state:

X(t) = (m(t), a(t), s(t))

Replay identity discipline:

B_A = B_B

SBM does not:

• modify classical mathematics
• redefine domain equations
• alter measured magnitude
• introduce predictive models
• perform probabilistic inference
• simulate future states
• inject control authority
• guarantee safety outcomes

SBM governs deterministic structural observability — not causation.

Conformance

An implementation conforms to the SBM Open Standard if it:

• Preserves magnitude exactly:
phi((m,a,s)) = m

• Uses deterministic bounded horizon evaluation H

• Maintains finite structural alphabet discipline

• Implements deterministic structural state transitions

• Produces byte-identical artifacts under independent replay:
B_A = B_B

• Avoids probabilistic or tolerance-based arbitration

Any implementation introducing:

• randomness
• probabilistic inference
• adaptive thresholds
• predictive extrapolation
• tolerance-based comparison
• nondeterministic output ordering
• runtime alphabet expansion
• magnitude modification

does not conform to the SBM Open Standard.

Independent implementations are permitted and encouraged.

